Negroes view campus
with mixed emotions [Article title; note: above 3 columns of text]
[note: inserted space]
By HOLLACE GOLDBERG [Author name; note: above first column]
[note: inserted space]
[First column]
• [correction: replace bullet point with double quotation mark] I was shaving in the dorm one
day,* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] related a Negro boy, ' [correction: replace single quotation mark with double quotation mark] and
I cut myself. A friend who was
sitting nearby joked with me
and said, ‘Gee, I didn’t know you
had red blood. My mother al­
ways told me it was blue.’ * [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Turning to his friend, the
Negro youth replied, * [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] Now that
you see it’s red, think of all the
other lies your mother might
have told you."
This is what the Negro some­
times encounters on campus.
But he knows that a jovial return
[note: inserted space]
[Second column]
or a friendly innuendo may serve
to enlighten a white person’s
attitudes and teach him what the
black man is like and what he is
not like.
Negroes on campus who mix
socially and academically with
whites and also stay away from
large associations of Negroes
feel that they are recognized as
students — [correction: insert space] not as •Negro* [note: non-matching punctuation marks] stu­
dents. As rapport develops be­
tween these Negroes and their
white colleagues, race becomes
just another topic for dormitory
bull sessions and jests.
Two colored girls in Wicomico [Place name]
[note: inserted space]
[Third column]
one day plastered Black Power
signs all over their hall. “ft [correction: replace ft with It] was
fun/ [correction: delete forward slash and insert double quotation mark] reports prankster Carolyn [Name],
a freshman from Baltimore [Place name], for
in reply to this stunt, the white
girls “dressed up in paper bags,
pretending they were a (Ku Klux)
Klan [Name of white supremacy group].* [correction: delete asterisk and insert double quotation mark]
The hooded WASPS [Acronym] sprinkled
perfume on the floor in the shape
of a cross and set fire to it. “It
really startled usP [correction: delete P] exclaimed
Carolyn [Name].
• [correction: replace bullet point with double quotation mark] We kid around a lot in the
dorm," related Bronwyn [Name], a junior.
• [correction: replace bullet point with double quotation mark] We sing * [correction: replace asterisk with single quotation mark] We Shall overcome.’ • [correction: replace bullet point with double quotation mark]
Songs and jokes, she says, don’t
offend her, for she does not "look
on the bad side about what other
people say about me."
Some other Negro students find
adjustment to College Park diffi­
cult. Betty [Name], who is 28 years old,
married and a native of Cali­
fornia [Place name], finds an “extremely
hostile* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] attitude about the
campus. “There are certain
vibrations you can feel.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Betty [Name] recalls an incident she
had with an advisor. During
registration week, she went to
him twice with scheduling dilem­
mas. “He was very nasty,* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] she
recalled, biting her lower lip and
widening her very expressive
eyes. “I told him I had to take
this course. He threw my (drop­
add) slip at me. . .1 [correction: replace 1 with I] thought it
was terribly unprofessional for
an advisor to extend this sort of
treatment.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Betty feels that her race did
play a causative factor toward
this discourteous treatment. “I
do have a basis for comparison,* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
she explained. She was raised
in an integrated community, has
traveled through Europe [Place name] with her
husband, attended San Francisco
State College [Name of College] and Hunter College [Name of College]
and interdated in her high school
and earlier college years.
