‘This is the first time I feel Negro’ [Pull quote; note: above all 4 columns]
(Continued from page 1)
[note: inserted space]
[First column]
• [correction: replace bullet point with double quotation mark] I find It [correction: replace It with it] extremely difficult to estab­
lish any form of communication with
some of the teachers and advisors here,* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
she said. “Students, basically, »ve [correction: are]
friendly, receptive, and warm. Bui [correction: But], in
some instances, there is hesitancy. . . I
don't think they know how to respond to
a Negro.* [replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Betty [Name] has run into trouble securing
rides from the commuters' carpool serv­
ice. A few times, she was able to arrange
rides over the telephone. However,
when she met her future commuting
companions they would frequently “begin
to make excuses,* [replace asterisk with double quotation mark] and Betty had no
ride.
Resulting from her academic and
social contacts, Betty [Name] concludes that,
“When you are brought up in an Inte­
grated situation, you act as an individual.
You are not Negro or white. But here
... in the South. . . and on this campus
... I feel lam [correction: I am] treading on white man's
territory. . .This is the first time I
feel Negro.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Also noting a discernible line between
the races, but holding a different view­
point is a 28 year-old male student who
works full time off campus.
What's so overwhelming about feeling
like a Negro, he questioned. “Isn't
there a distinction* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] between Negroes and
whites?
With a wholly different frame of mind
is Harry [Name], a lively, congenial sophomore
who commutes to school and takes photo­
graphs for campus publications. “I am
not a Negro on a white campus!* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] he
asserts.
• [correction: replace bullet point with double quotation mark] I don't think this is a white campus
. . . and I don't go for this stuff that the
Negro doesn’t have as much chance as
everyone else out here. He does.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
A native of Wisconsin and formerly a
nine-year resident of Little Rock, Ark. [Place name],
Harry [Name] says, “Because of the way my
family brought me up. . .1 [correction: replace 1 with I] have never
felt inferior to anybody. Some Negroes
do feel inferior. Some feel mid way.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
A Negro who feels cunningly daring is
Dave [Name]. Dave [Name] has skin brown as chocolate,
teeth white as snow and a smile that
signals immediate rapport with his
environment.
“Maryland is a conservative campus,* [replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
he notes. “You can’t very well walk out
of your race. I was told a lot of tales
[note: inserted space]
[Second column]
before I came here. ‘You can’t do this.
You can’t do that.’ I feel, though, that
there is an atmosphere here and an
opportunity to participate in just about
anything.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Dave [Name] has been active in dormitory
sports, house rules committee, powder­
puff football, dormitory parties and
homecoming preparations.
Socially, Dave [Name] goes out with whites
and Negroes. “I've gone steady with
white girls, Jewish girls,* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] he said,
adding, “I guess I am a gregarious
fellow. I interrelate easily.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] “But I
use my intellect before I jump. Every­
one gets slapped in the face a few times.
So you use some discretion.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
In class, for example, “If your grade
is tottering. . . and your prof talks with
a little bit of a Southern accent. . . you
don’t talk to Sally during the lecture.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Two female Negro students, however,
disagree with Dave’s [Name] classroom obser­
vation. “If you prove yourself to the
teacher," feels Bronwyn [Name], “there is noth­
ing the teacher can do against you.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
“I have encountered nothing (prejudi­
cial) whatsoever,* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] related Kathleen, a
junior majoring in marketing and a
transfer student from the University of
Maryland [Name of College] in Munich, Germany [Place name]. “I have
yet to find an Inkling [correction: replace Inkling with inkling] that such a thing
exists as far as teaching is concerned.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Rich [Name], a 26 year-old Business Student
recalls, “There were a couple of courses
I have taken here where I felt I had
gotten a raw deal... I have only run
across two professors I can really sit
down and talk to here in BPA [Acronym].* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Betty [Name], the attractive housewife-student
from California agrees. “I don’t expect
to get the benefit of the doubt if I am
borderline.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Discussing classroom interaction
among students, some Negroes find they
are stared at if race is discussed during
a lecture. Other Negroes notice nothing
of the sort.
• [correction: replace bullet point with double quotation mark] The kids don’t stare at me. They
don’t even look up,* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] laughed a pretty
Junior who commutes to school from
Laurel [Place]. “If they do, I don’t catch them
staring!* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
“Sometimes it hits me that I am the
only Negro in a class,* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] relates another
[note: inserted space]
[Third column]
Negro. * [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark] lt [correction: replace lt with It] doesn't make me shrink. I
am always working harder because I
always feel I have to prove myself to
white people. I have to show them that I
live as well as they do, maybe better.
I am not a dumb, ignorant Negro. I feel
that I have to prove this to them,* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
Though the Negroes on campus have
[note: inserted space]
[Fourth column]
different experiences and perceptions to
relate, they generally agree on one com­
mon theme. As one freshman comment­
ed, “When you have more and more
contact with Negro people, then you
don’t have as many preconceptions. Why?
Because the preconceptions all fall
apart.* [correction: replace asterisk with double quotation mark]
